attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Otto, Ernst, Erwin, Frieda, Gerhard, Gottlieb, Gunther, Hans, Heinz, Reinhold, Udo.","German: topographic name for someone who lived by woods used as pasture, from Middle High German <i>hart</i>.","German: from a short form of an ancient Germanic compound personal name beginning with <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hart","meanings":["English and North German: nickname from Middle English <i>hert</i> (Old English <i>heorot</i>), Middle Low German <i>hërte</i>, <i>harte</i> ‘hart, stag’, perhaps for a quick-footed or timorous individual.","German: variant of   Hardt   1 and 2. It is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine).","Jewish (Ashkenazic): artificial name or nickname from German and Yiddish <i>hart</i> ‘hard’."]},{"name":"Harth","meanings":["German: variant of   Hardt   1 and 2.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): variant of   Hart  ."]},{"name":"Hort","meanings":["South German: variant of   Hardt   1.","English (Gloucestershire): variant of   Hart  ."]}]},{"name":"Sandde","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Possibly an altered form of German <b>Sandel</b>, a habitational name from Sandel in Lower Saxony.","English: variant of   Sandell  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Sandell","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Nils, Anders, Thor.","Swedish: ornamental name from <i>sand</i> ‘sand’ + the suffix <i>-ell</i>, a derivative of the Latin adjectival ending <i>-elius</i>. The original humanistic form of the surname, <b>Sandelius</b>, is still common in Sweden.","English: from Middle English <i>sand</i> ‘sand’ + <i>hil(le)</i>, <i>hul(le)</i> ‘hill’ or <i>helde</i>, <i>hilde</i>, <i>hulde</i> ‘slope’. The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived on or near a sandy hill or sandy slope, or habitational, from a place so named, such as Sandhill, in Worth (Sussex) or Sandhill, in East Grinstead (Sussex)."]}]},{"name":"Hardd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: transferred use of the surname, in origin a nickname for a brave or stout‐hearted man (from Middle English, Old French <i>hardi</i>, of Germanic origin)."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sandde Hardd ap Caradog Hardd was born about 1075, his father, Caradog Hardd ap Gwydr, was 51 and his mother, Argharad Angh Brochwel, was 36. He had at least 1 son with Angharad ferch Brochwel of Llwydiarth Anglesey. He died in 1150, at the age of 76, and was buried in Burton, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1075  but 1165 suggested by Ancient Welsh Studies–1150":"umbes 1075–1150","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1075–1150":"1075–1150","1040–Female":"1040–Surnud","1105–1180":"1105–1180","1107–1179":"1107–1179","1109–Male":"1109–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1025–Male":"1025–Surnud","about 1075  but 1165 suggested by Ancient Welsh Studies":"umbes 1075","1075":"1075","1150":"1150","1040":"1040","1060":"1060","1180":"1180","1107":"1107","1107or 1195":"1107","1105":"1105","1025":"1025","1179":"1179","about 1105 ":"umbes 1105","before 1040":"enne 1040","1109 ":"1109","1109":"1109",", Burton, Co. Denbigh, Wales":"Burton, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Burton, Denbighshire, Wales":"Burton, Denbighshire, Wales","Europe":"Europe","Clwyd, Flintshire, Wales":"Clwyd, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1075  but 1165 suggested by Ancient Welsh Studies–1150":"noin 1075–1150","1060–Male":"1060–Kuollut","1075–1150":"1075–1150","1040–Female":"1040–Kuollut","1105–1180":"1105–1180","1107–1179":"1107–1179","1109–Male":"1109–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1025–Male":"1025–Kuollut","about 1075  but 1165 suggested by Ancient Welsh Studies":"noin 1075","1075":"1075","1150":"1150","1040":"1040","1060":"1060","1180":"1180","1107":"1107","1107or 1195":"1107","1105":